From b4e2b6c6501489b8d86b0d3c1730b93982d9faf0 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Remco van Mook <remco@asteroidhq.com>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 22:48:16 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] network: support IPv6-resolved IPv4 gateway (192.0.0.11)

Implement the host-side behaviour of
draft-vanmook-intarea-ipv6-resolved-gateway behind a new opt-in
[DHCPv4] UseIPv6ResolvedGateway= boolean (default false): when enabled
and a DHCPv4 lease designates the special-purpose address 192.0.0.11 as
the router (option 3), the IPv4 default route is not installed with an
ARP-resolved IPv4 next hop. Instead, the next hop is set to the IPv6
default router selected from the NDisc default router list per RFC 4191
preference (ties broken deterministically by lowest router address),
and the route is programmed with an IPv6 nexthop (RTA_VIA, Linux 5.2+),
so the kernel resolves the link-layer address via Neighbor Discovery.
No ARP is performed, and no IPv4 subnet is required on the link.

Because networkd owns both the DHCPv4 client and the NDisc state in a
single process, the IPv4 default route is re-evaluated whenever the
default router list changes: on RA reception and on router lifetime
expiry. If no IPv6 default router is known when the lease is processed,
route installation is deferred until the first RA arrives. RFC 3442
precedence of classless static routes over the Router option is
preserved. Lease renewal and loss are covered by the existing DHCPv4
mark/sweep of routes with source NETWORK_CONFIG_SOURCE_DHCP4; a router
change away from the sentinel drops the stale RTA_VIA route through the
same mechanism.

Kernels older than 5.2 are detected via a one-time version check and
the route is skipped with a warning; vendor backports are still caught
by the netlink error path. An integration test covers route
installation via the built-in DHCP server (Router=192.0.0.11) combined
with IPv6SendRA=, and re-evaluation across an RA refresh.
